<article id="post-597" class="post-597 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized">
					
	<div class="entry-inner">
		
<header class="entry-header">
			<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/" title="Permalink to Protect your backups from ransomware" rel="bookmark">Protect your backups from ransomware</a></h1>
	
		<div class="entry-meta">
		Posted on <a href="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/" title="8:11 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2018-02-09T20:11:32+00:00" pubdate>February 9, 2018</time></a><span class="byline"> by <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://www.backupcentral.com/author/admin/" title="View all posts by W. Curtis Preston" rel="author">W. Curtis Preston</a></span></span>	</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->	
				<div class="entry-content">
			<p>Don&#8217;t get your backup advice from security people. That&#8217;s how I felt reading what started out as a <a href="http://www.information-age.com/cyber-security-migrating-data-to-prevent-ransomware-attacks-123470694/">really good article</a> about protecting your systems from ransomware.  It was all great until he started talking about how to configure your backup system.  He had no idea what he was talking about. But now I&#8217;m going to give you security advice about your backup system, so take it with a grain of salt.</p>
<h2>Windows backup servers are risky</h2>
<p><img data-attachment-id="598" data-permalink="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/shutterstock_618400631/#main" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?fit=1000%2C667" data-orig-size="1000,667" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="risky windows" data-image-description data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-large-file="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?fit=620%2C414" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-598" src="http://www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/plugins/jetpack/modules/lazy-images/images/1x1.trans.gif" alt width="620" height="414" data-recalc-dims="1" data-lazy-src="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=620%2C414" data-lazy-srcset="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?w=1000 1000w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=300%2C200 300w, https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=768%2C512 768w, https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=660%2C440 660w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=240%2C160 240w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px"><noscript><img data-attachment-id="598" data-permalink="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/shutterstock_618400631/#main" data-orig-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?fit=1000%2C667" data-orig-size="1000,667" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="risky windows" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-large-file="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?fit=620%2C414" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-598" src="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=620%2C414" alt="" width="620" height="414" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?w=1000 1000w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=300%2C200 300w, https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=768%2C512 768w, https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=660%2C440 660w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_618400631.jpg?resize=240%2C160 240w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></noscript></p>
<p>Windows-based backup products that store data in a directory are a huge security risk. In fact, many customers of such products have already reported my worst fears: their backups were encrypted with the same ransomware that infected their servers.</p>
<p>This isn&#8217;t an anti-Windows rant, or an anti-BackupProductX rant. It&#8217;s simply acknowledging the elephant in the room.</p>
<ol>
<li>If your backup server is accessible via the same network your computers are on, it can be attacked via the same things that attack your computers.</li>
<li>If your backup server runs the same OS as your computers – especially if it&#8217;s the OS that most ransomware attacks happen on (Windows) – it can be infected with the same ransomware</li>
<li>If your backups are stored in a directory (as opposed to a tape drive, an S3 object, or a smart appliance <em>not</em> accessible via SMB/NFS), they can be infected if your backup server is infected.</li>
<li>If your backups are stored on a network mount via NFS/SMB, you&#8217;re giving the ransomware even more ways to attack you.</li>
</ol>
<h2>What should you do?</h2>
<p><img data-attachment-id="599" data-permalink="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/shutterstock_569097694/#main" data-orig-file="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?fit=1000%2C667" data-orig-size="1000,667" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="what to do" data-image-description data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-large-file="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?fit=620%2C414" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-599" src="http://www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/plugins/jetpack/modules/lazy-images/images/1x1.trans.gif" alt width="620" height="414" data-recalc-dims="1" data-lazy-src="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=620%2C414" data-lazy-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?w=1000 1000w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=300%2C200 300w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=768%2C512 768w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=660%2C440 660w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=240%2C160 240w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px"><noscript><img data-attachment-id="599" data-permalink="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/shutterstock_569097694/#main" data-orig-file="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?fit=1000%2C667" data-orig-size="1000,667" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="what to do" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-large-file="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?fit=620%2C414" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-599" src="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=620%2C414" alt="" width="620" height="414" srcset="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?w=1000 1000w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=300%2C200 300w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=768%2C512 768w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=660%2C440 660w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_569097694.jpg?resize=240%2C160 240w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></noscript></p>
<p>I don&#8217;t want to be guilty of doing what the security guy did, so I&#8217;ll say this: research what you can do to protect your systems from ransomware. But I&#8217;ll do my best to give some general advice.</p>
<p>I know the best advice I&#8217;ve read is to keep up-to-date on patches and to disable Remote Desktop Management on Windows.  There are also default SMB shares in Windows that should be disabled.</p>
<p>You can also make sure that your backups aren&#8217;t just stored in a directory. Unfortunately, that&#8217;s the default setup for most inexpensive backup software products. You need to investigate if the software you&#8217;re using supports another way to store backups.  If not, it&#8217;s time to think about a different product.</p>
<p>The same goes true for those currently storing backups on an NFS/SMB share. Investigate if your backup software has the ability to store backups on that device without using NFS/SMB. If not, make sure you lock down that share as much as you can. Again, if not, it&#8217;s time to think about another backup product.</p>
<h2>Consider a cloud data protection service</h2>
<p><img data-attachment-id="600" data-permalink="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/shutterstock_382087234/#main" data-orig-file="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?fit=1000%2C667" data-orig-size="1000,667" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="cloud services" data-image-description data-medium-file="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?fit=620%2C414" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-600" src="http://www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/plugins/jetpack/modules/lazy-images/images/1x1.trans.gif" alt width="620" height="414" data-recalc-dims="1" data-lazy-src="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=620%2C414" data-lazy-srcset="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?w=1000 1000w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=300%2C200 300w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=768%2C512 768w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=660%2C440 660w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=240%2C160 240w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px"><noscript><img data-attachment-id="600" data-permalink="http://www.backupcentral.com/protect-your-backups-from-ransomware/shutterstock_382087234/#main" data-orig-file="https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?fit=1000%2C667" data-orig-size="1000,667" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="cloud services" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?fit=300%2C200" data-large-file="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?fit=620%2C414" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-600" src="https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=620%2C414" alt="" width="620" height="414" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?w=1000 1000w, https://i2.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=300%2C200 300w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=768%2C512 768w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=660%2C440 660w, https://i1.wp.com/www.backupcentral.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/shutterstock_382087234.jpg?resize=240%2C160 240w" sizes="(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px" data-recalc-dims="1" /></noscript></p>
<p>A <em>true</em> cloud-based data protection service might be the best way to do this.  In a true cloud-based system, you never see the backup servers. You don&#8217;t know what they are and never login to them. You login to a web-based portal, and the actual servers that make this happen are completely invisible to you.  (Similar to the way the servers that make salesforce.com happen are invisible to you.)</p>
<p>If your backup servers are invisible to you, they&#8217;re invisible to your attackers. If there&#8217;s no way to directly access your backup – unless you&#8217;ve specifically setup such access for a recovery or DR test – then ransomware can&#8217;t get to those backups either.</p>
<p>It should go without saying that this recommendation does not apply if your &#8220;cloud&#8221; data protection vendor is just putting backup software on VMs that you manage in the cloud – what many have dubbed &#8220;cloud washing.&#8221; If you&#8217;re seeing your backup servers as VMs in the cloud, they&#8217;re just as much of a risk as they are if they were in your data centers. It&#8217;s on the reasons why these cloud washing vendors aren&#8217;t really giving you the full benefit of the cloud if all they&#8217;re doing is putting VMs up there.</p>
<p>----- Signature and Disclaimer -----</p>

